Today we learn one of the MOST IMPORTANT topics for coding rounds:

👉 Loops (Repetition = Power in programming)

🧠 Concept 1: for Loop (Controlled Repetition)
✅ What it is

👉 Used when you know how many times to repeat

for (initialization; condition; update) {
    // code
}
💡 Real-World Analogy

Think like this:

👉 You are doing 10 push-ups 💪

Start → 1

Check → until 10

Increase → +1

That’s exactly a for loop.

⚙️ Why it works (Important 🔥)
for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++)

Break it mentally:

int i = 1 → start

i <= 5 → check

i++ → update

👉 Loop runs until condition becomes FALSE

🔥 Internal Flow (INTERVIEW IMPORTANT)

Order:

👉 Initialization → Condition → Body → Update → Condition → ...

💻 Example
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
        printf("%d ", i);
    }
    return 0;
}

👉 Output:

1 2 3 4 5
🔗 Connection to what you know

Same in Java/C++

Python:

for i in range(1,6):

👉 C gives you full control manually

🧠 Memory Trick

👉 Remember:

“for = when count is known”

🧠 Concept 2: while Loop (Condition-Based Repetition)
✅ What it is

👉 Used when you don’t know how many times to repeat

while (condition) {
    // code
}
💡 Real-World Analogy

👉 Think:

“Keep eating 🍕 until you are full”

You don’t know exact count.

⚙️ Why it works (Important 🔥)
int i = 1;
while (i <= 5)

👉 Condition checked first
👉 If TRUE → runs
👉 If FALSE → stops

⚠️ MOST COMMON MISTAKE (VERY IMPORTANT)

👉 Forgetting update → infinite loop

while (i <= 5) {
    printf("%d", i);
}

❌ i never changes → runs forever

💻 Example
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int i = 1;

    while (i <= 5) {
        printf("%d ", i);
        i++;
    }

    return 0;
}
🔗 Connection to what you know

Same in Java/C++

Python:

while i <= 5:
🧠 Memory Trick

👉 Remember:

“while = when condition matters more than count”

⚡ BONUS (INTERVIEW GOLD)
Difference: for vs while
for loop	while loop
Known iterations	Unknown iterations
Compact	Flexible
Used in counting	Used in conditions
🎯 Interview Insight (VERY IMPORTANT)

They may ask:

❓ Difference between for and while?
❓ When to use which?
❓ What causes infinite loop?

👉 Now you understand, not memorize.

